2 HOUSE BILL 882
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Health – General
4 20–2203.
5 State and local agencies shall use plain language in public communications about
6 health, health insurance, safety, and social services benefits.
7 20–2204.
8 (a) The University of Maryland Herschel S. Horowitz Center for Health Literacy
9 is designated as the State’s Consumer Health Information Hub.
10 (b) The purpose of the Hub is to promote and ensure public access to accurate,
11 consistent, evidence–based, plain–language information in preferred languages to inform
12 decisions about health, safety, and social services benefits.
13 (c) [The] TO THE EXTENT FUNDING IS AVAILABLE, THE Hub shall:
14 (1) Protect and promote public health by engaging with State and local
15 government agencies, health systems, nonprofit and community–based organizations, and
16 other entities to carry out the Hub’s purpose and duties under this subtitle;
17 (2) Establish and promote health literacy criteria, certifications, and best
18 practices that advance the effectiveness of the State’s health care system;
19 (3) Identify health literacy challenges and provide recommendations to
20 agencies and organizations on how to address the challenges, including by improving
21 programs and materials to provide the public with access to plain–language health, safety,
22 and social services benefits information;
23 (4) Monitor and report on the use of health literacy and plain–language
24 initiatives and support public reporting of vital public health information, including health
25 care quality reports from the Maryland Health Care Commission; and
26 (5) Support the identification and ongoing training of health literacy
27 officers in State and local agencies.
28 (d) [For fiscal year 2024 and each fiscal year thereafter, the Governor shall
29 include in the annual budget bill an appropriation of $350,000 to the Hub.
30 (e)] On or before July 1 each year, beginning in 2024, the Hub shall submit a
31 report to the Senate Finance Committee and the House Health [and Government
32 Operations] Committee, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, on

HOUSE BILL 882 3
1 the implementation of this subtitle, including the status of statewide health literacy efforts
2 and materials provided.
3 Chapter 679 of the Acts of 2022
4 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
5 1, 2022. [It shall remain effective for a period of 4 years and, at the end of June 30, 2026,
6 this Act, with no further action required by the General Assembly, shall be abrogated and
7 of no further force and effect.]
8 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
9 1, 2026.
